WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.700
So, that's enough on class components.

00:02.700 --> 00:05.300
We shall never speak of it again.

00:05.300 --> 00:10.420
Let's go actually use it though.

00:10.420 --> 00:14.180
Let's go to pass order route.

00:14.180 --> 00:18.180
We're going to import our error boundary at the top.

00:18.180 --> 00:25.380
Import error boundary from error boundary and we're going to, one interesting thing

00:25.380 --> 00:33.160
about error boundaries, because of the way that the errors work, you can't put the error

00:33.160 --> 00:34.160
boundary here.

00:34.160 --> 00:36.680
So, I can't just say like error boundary here.

00:36.680 --> 00:38.340
Why?

00:38.340 --> 00:42.200
Because if this component has an error, the whole component blows up, right?

00:42.200 --> 00:46.400
So, I need to put it in a function component above it, right, so that I can catch things

00:46.400 --> 00:47.400
inside of it.

00:47.400 --> 00:49.660
Does that make sense?

00:49.660 --> 00:52.680
It's like you have to put things inside of the try for the catch to work.

00:52.680 --> 00:54.440
That's essentially what I'm saying.

00:55.020 --> 01:00.020
So, let me show you what I mean and then you can give me those perpex glances again.

01:00.020 --> 01:03.420
So, I'm going to put a, let's just do it above.

01:03.420 --> 01:04.420
I think I have it above.

01:04.420 --> 01:05.660
So, it's a little bit more clear.

01:05.660 --> 01:17.620
So, I'm going to write another function here called error boundary wrapped past order routes.

01:17.620 --> 01:25.440
And you're just going to say return error boundary and then inside of that past order

01:25.440 --> 01:33.280
route and then error boundary is going to be the thing that we actually export.

01:33.280 --> 01:42.880
So, the error boundary can only catch things that are being rendered inside of it.

01:42.880 --> 01:47.520
And so, if it's on the same level of this, so if it was actually inside of past order,

01:47.540 --> 01:49.660
it wouldn't get the opportunity to catch the error.

01:49.660 --> 01:53.260
So, it has to be outside of it.

01:53.260 --> 01:57.020
Which is why we have to have two components here and then we're actually shipping the

01:57.020 --> 01:59.460
error boundary one.

01:59.460 --> 02:07.540
Now, some of you might say, but Brian, what if there's being props passed into this?

02:07.540 --> 02:11.500
In this case, we're not passing any props into it, but what if we were, right?

02:11.500 --> 02:18.480
So, all you have to do here is we take in props here at this level and then there's

02:18.480 --> 02:21.280
this something here called the spread operator that works.

02:21.280 --> 02:26.560
And we're going to say whatever props we got here, just pass them on through.

02:26.560 --> 02:28.680
Now, why didn't I teach you this earlier?

02:28.680 --> 02:31.720
You're probably thinking, spread operator looks pretty cool.

02:31.720 --> 02:34.400
Why don't we use that a lot of places?

02:34.400 --> 02:38.240
And I intentionally do that because I don't want you to use it that frequently, right?

02:38.260 --> 02:42.660
It is nice that it's just saying like, hey, here's a grab bag of things, kind of spread

02:42.660 --> 02:43.660
them out.

02:43.660 --> 02:51.140
So, imagine this props, for example, was something like, I don't even comment this, it could

02:51.140 --> 03:02.340
be like, stuff, cool, other stuff, not cool, right?

03:02.720 --> 03:10.440
You could come in here and actually just do stuff equals props dot stuff and other stuff

03:10.440 --> 03:14.360
equals props dot other stuff, right?

03:14.360 --> 03:19.120
And you could go be more explicit about that, that's totally fine as well, but you might

03:19.120 --> 03:23.920
be like, it looks nicer to do just the spread operator.

03:23.920 --> 03:31.160
This makes it so opaque to read though, so this, for things that you're actually passing

03:31.180 --> 03:37.660
stuff into explicitly, I want to see this because it makes me know this is the API that

03:37.660 --> 03:42.540
I'm adhering to, these are like where the data from is coming from and where it's going.

03:42.540 --> 03:46.980
Again, the explicitness of React is one of its superpowers.

03:46.980 --> 03:58.020
And so by hiding it behind dot dot dot props like this, you make it pretty opaque of like,

03:58.020 --> 04:01.560
what is coming from where and where is it going?

04:01.560 --> 04:07.320
The only reason in this particular case that I am okay with the spread operator is that

04:07.320 --> 04:11.920
this particular component is meant to be a pass through, it's actually not meant to know

04:11.920 --> 04:15.040
about what's coming into it and where it's going, right?

04:15.040 --> 04:18.760
It's literally just meant to be going for like connecting two pipes together.

04:18.760 --> 04:23.720
And so this actually makes this less clear, right?

04:23.720 --> 04:27.320
And this is clear, this is a clear communication to the future developer, the reading this,

04:27.320 --> 04:29.700
which is likely yourself, right?

04:29.700 --> 04:33.540
That this isn't supposed to know where it's coming through it, right?

04:33.540 --> 04:34.860
It's just supposed to be the pass through.

04:34.860 --> 04:43.980
Do you know why AirBoundaries were left out of the new React or why they still require

04:43.980 --> 04:45.460
the classical component?

04:45.460 --> 04:48.580
It's a good question.

04:48.580 --> 04:54.260
My reading on the situation, which is Brian reading between the lines, is they didn't

04:54.320 --> 05:00.280
really have a elegant way to handle it that was better than doing it in the class component

05:00.280 --> 05:01.280
way.

05:01.280 --> 05:04.800
Because it doesn't have a get derived state from, it doesn't have all the things that

05:04.800 --> 05:08.240
a class will have.

05:08.240 --> 05:11.720
And so because of that, they decided like, well, we're going to leave in class components.

05:11.720 --> 05:18.260
They didn't have any intent to deprecate class components anyway.

05:18.640 --> 05:25.400
They left it that because, yeah, they would have made the library worse by trying to force

05:25.400 --> 05:27.680
it into this other pattern.

05:27.680 --> 05:32.440
And because they published that like React AirBoundary component, everyone can just use

05:32.440 --> 05:33.440
that.

05:33.440 --> 05:37.240
And can I just put an AirBoundary in my route?

05:37.240 --> 05:38.240
Sure can.

05:38.240 --> 05:39.240
People do it.

05:39.240 --> 05:41.440
And just have one AirBoundary handle everything?

05:41.440 --> 05:44.280
Yeah, you could definitely, I would put it here probably at root.

05:45.260 --> 05:52.620
Yeah, I would put it here and you could just do like AirBoundary right there, catch everything.

05:52.620 --> 05:55.860
If that was appropriate for you, yeah, hell yeah, absolutely.

05:55.860 --> 05:59.980
So let's actually like, make it work because, or like, try it.

06:08.980 --> 06:09.980
There you go.

06:09.980 --> 06:14.480
OMG, LOL, WTF.

06:14.480 --> 06:17.480
Is that our AirBoundary?

06:17.480 --> 06:21.740
There you go.

